                              THE KILLERS\
\
\
THE door of Henry\'92s lunch-room opened and two men came in. They sat down\
at the counter.\
\
\'93What\'92s yours?\'94 George asked them.\
\
\'93I don\'92t know,\'94 one of the men said. \'93What do you want to eat, Al?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know,\'94 said Al. \'93I don\'92t know what I want to eat.\'94\
\
Outside it was getting dark. The street-light came on outside the\
window. The two men at the counter read the menu. From the other end of\
the counter Nick Adams watched them. He had been talking to George when\
they came in.\
\
\'93I\'92ll have a roast pork tenderloin with apple sauce and mashed\
potatoes,\'94 the first man said.\
\
\'93It isn\'92t ready yet.\'94\
\
\'93What the hell do you put it on the card for?\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s the dinner,\'94 George explained. \'93You can get that at six\
o\'92clock.\'94\
\
George looked at the clock on the wall behind the counter.\
\
\'93It\'92s five o\'92clock.\'94\
\
\'93The clock says twenty minutes past five,\'94 the second man said.\
\
\'93It\'92s twenty minutes fast.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, to hell with the clock,\'94 the first man said. \'93What have you got to\
eat?\'94\
\
\'93I can give you any kind of sandwiches,\'94 George said. \'93You can have ham\
and eggs, bacon and eggs, liver and bacon, or a steak.\'94\
\
\'93Give me chicken croquettes with green peas and cream sauce and mashed\
potatoes.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s the dinner.\'94\
\
\'93Everything we want\'92s the dinner, eh? That\'92s the way you work it.\'94\
\
\'93I can give you ham and eggs, bacon and eggs, liver\'97\'97\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll take ham and eggs,\'94 the man called Al said. He wore a derby hat\
and a black overcoat buttoned across the chest. His face was small and\
white and he had tight lips. He wore a silk muffler and gloves.\
\
\'93Give me bacon and eggs,\'94 said the other man. He was about the same size\
as Al. Their faces were different, but they were dressed like twins.\
Both wore overcoats too tight for them. They sat leaning forward, their\
elbows on the counter.\
\
\'93Got anything to drink?\'94 Al asked.\
\
\'93Silver beer, bevo, ginger-ale,\'94 George said.\
\
\'93I mean you got anything to _drink_?\'94\
\
\'93Just those I said.\'94\
\
\'93This is a hot town,\'94 said the other. \'93What do they call it?\'94\
\
\'93Summit.\'94\
\
\'93Ever hear of it?\'94 Al asked his friend.\
\
\'93No,\'94 said the friend.\
\
\'93What do you do here nights?\'94 Al asked.\
\
\'93They eat the dinner,\'94 his friend said. \'93They all come here and eat the\
big dinner.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s right,\'94 George said.\
\
\'93So you think that\'92s right?\'94 Al asked George.\
\
\'93Sure.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re a pretty bright boy, aren\'92t you?\'94\
\
\'93Sure,\'94 said George.\
\
\'93Well, you\'92re not,\'94 said the other little man. \'93Is he, Al?\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s dumb,\'94 said Al. He turned to Nick. \'93What\'92s your name?\'94\
\
\'93Adams.\'94\
\
\'93Another bright boy,\'94 Al said. \'93Ain\'92t he a bright boy, Max?\'94\
\
\'93The town\'92s full of bright boys,\'94 Max said.\
\
George put the two platters, one of ham and eggs, the other of bacon and\
eggs, on the counter. He set down two side-dishes of fried potatoes and\
closed the wicket into the kitchen.\
\
\'93Which is yours?\'94 he asked Al.\
\
\'93Don\'92t you remember?\'94\
\
\'93Ham and eggs.\'94\
\
\'93Just a bright boy,\'94 Max said. He leaned forward and took the ham and\
eggs. Both men ate with their gloves on. George watched them eat.\
\
\'93What are _you_ looking at?\'94 Max looked at George.\
\
\'93Nothing.\'94\
\
\'93The hell you were. You were looking at me.\'94\
\
\'93Maybe the boy meant it for a joke, Max,\'94 Al said.\
\
George laughed.\
\
\'93_You_ don\'92t have to laugh,\'94 Max said to him. \'93_You_ don\'92t have to laugh\
at all, see?\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 said George.\
\
\'93So he thinks it\'92s all right.\'94 Max turned to Al. \'93He thinks it\'92s all\
right. That\'92s a good one.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, he\'92s a thinker,\'94 Al said. They went on eating.\
\
\'93What\'92s the bright boy\'92s name down the counter?\'94 Al asked Max.\
\
\'93Hey, bright boy,\'94 Max said to Nick. \'93You go around on the other side of\
the counter with your boy friend.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s the idea?\'94 Nick asked.\
\
\'93There isn\'92t any idea.\'94\
\
\'93You better go around, bright boy,\'94 Al said. Nick went around behind the\
counter.\
\
\'93What\'92s the idea?\'94 George asked.\
\
\'93None of your damn business,\'94 Al said. \'93Who\'92s out in the kitchen?\'94\
\
\'93The nigger.\'94\
\
\'93What do you mean the nigger?\'94\
\
\'93The nigger that cooks.\'94\
\
\'93Tell him to come in.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s the idea?\'94\
\
\'93Tell him to come in.\'94\
\
\'93Where do you think you are?\'94\
\
\'93We know damn well where we are,\'94 the man called Max said. \'93Do we look\
silly?\'94\
\
\'93You talk silly,\'94 Al said to him. \'93What the hell do you argue with this\
kid for? Listen,\'94 he said to George, \'93tell the nigger to come out here.\'94\
\
\'93What are you going to do to him?\'94\
\
\'93Nothing. Use your head, bright boy. What would we do to a nigger?\'94\
\
George opened the slit that opened back into the kitchen. \'93Sam,\'94 he\
called. \'93Come in here a minute.\'94\
\
The door to the kitchen opened and the nigger came in. \'93What was it?\'94 he\
asked. The two men at the counter took a look at him.\
\
\'93All right, nigger. You stand right there,\'94 Al said.\
\
Sam, the nigger, standing in his apron, looked at the two men sitting at\
the counter. \'93Yes, sir,\'94 he said. Al got down from his stool.\
\
\'93I\'92m going back to the kitchen with the nigger and bright boy,\'94 he said.\
\'93Go on back to the kitchen, nigger. You go with him, bright boy.\'94 The\
little man walked after Nick and Sam, the cook, back into the kitchen.\
The door shut after them. The man called Max sat at the counter opposite\
George. He didn\'92t look at George but looked in the mirror that ran along\
back of the counter. Henry\'92s had been made over from a saloon into a\
lunch-counter.\
\
\'93Well, bright boy,\'94 Max said, looking into the mirror, \'93why don\'92t you\
say something?\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s it all about?\'94\
\
\'93Hey, Al,\'94 Max called, \'93bright boy wants to know what it\'92s all about.\'94\
\
\'93Why don\'92t you tell him?\'94 Al\'92s voice came from the kitchen.\
\
\'93What do you think it\'92s all about?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know.\'94\
\
\'93What do you think?\'94\
\
Max looked into the mirror all the time he was talking.\
\
\'93I wouldn\'92t say.\'94\
\
\'93Hey, Al, bright boy says he wouldn\'92t say what he thinks it\'92s all\
about.\'94\
\
\'93I can hear you, all right,\'94 Al said from the kitchen. He had propped\
open the slit that dishes passed through into the kitchen with a catsup\
bottle. \'93Listen, bright boy,\'94 he said from the kitchen to George. \'93Stand\
a little further along the bar. You move a little to the left, Max.\'94 He\
was like a photographer arranging for a group picture.\
\
\'93Talk to me, bright boy,\'94 Max said. \'93What do you think\'92s going to\
happen?\'94\
\
George did not say anything.\
\
\'93I\'92ll tell you,\'94 Max said. \'93We\'92re going to kill a Swede. Do you know a\
big Swede named Ole Andreson?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93He comes here to eat every night, don\'92t he?\'94\
\
\'93Sometimes he comes here.\'94\
\
\'93He comes here at six o\'92clock, don\'92t he?\'94\
\
\'93If he comes.\'94\
\
\'93We know all that, bright boy,\'94 Max said. \'93Talk about something else.\
Ever go to the movies?\'94\
\
\'93Once in a while.\'94\
\
\'93You ought to go to the movies more. The movies are fine for a bright\
boy like you.\'94\
\
\'93What are you going to kill Ole Andreson for? What did he ever do to\
you?\'94\
\
\'93He never had a chance to do anything to us. He never even seen us.\'94\
\
\'93And he\'92s only going to see us once,\'94 Al said from the kitchen.\
\
\'93What are you going to kill him for, then?\'94 George asked.\
\
\'93We\'92re killing him for a friend. Just to oblige a friend, bright boy.\'94\
\
\'93Shut up,\'94 said Al from the kitchen. \'93You talk too goddam much.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I got to keep bright boy amused. Don\'92t I, bright boy?\'94\
\
\'93You talk too damn much,\'94 Al said. \'93The nigger and my bright boy are\
amused by themselves. I got them tied up like a couple of girl friends\
in the convent.\'94\
\
\'93I suppose you were in a convent.\'94\
\
\'93You never know.\'94\
\
\'93You were in a kosher convent. That\'92s where you were.\'94\
\
George looked up at the clock.\
\
\'93If anybody comes in you tell them the cook is off, and if they keep\
after it, you tell them you\'92ll go back and cook yourself. Do you get\
that, bright boy?\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 George said. \'93What you going to do with us afterward?\'94\
\
\'93That\'92ll depend,\'94 Max said. \'93That\'92s one of those things you never know\
at the time.\'94\
\
George looked up at the clock. It was a quarter past six. The door from\
the street opened. A street-car motorman came in.\
\
\'93Hello, George,\'94 he said. \'93Can I get supper?\'94\
\
\'93Sam\'92s gone out,\'94 George said. \'93He\'92ll be back in about half an hour.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92d better go up the street,\'94 the motorman said. George looked at the\
clock. It was twenty minutes past six.\
\
\'93That was nice, bright boy,\'94 Max said. \'93You\'92re a regular little\
gentleman.\'94\
\
\'93He knew I\'92d blow his head off,\'94 Al said from the kitchen.\
\
\'93No,\'94 said Max. \'93It ain\'92t that. Bright boy is nice. He\'92s a nice boy. I\
like him.\'94\
\
At six-fifty-five George said: \'93He\'92s not coming.\'94\
\
Two other people had been in the lunch-room. Once George had gone out to\
the kitchen and made a ham-and-egg sandwich \'93to go\'94 that a man wanted to\
take with him. Inside the kitchen he saw Al, his derby hat tipped back,\
sitting on a stool beside the wicket with the muzzle of a sawed-off\
shotgun resting on the ledge. Nick and the cook were back to back in the\
corner, a towel tied in each of their mouths. George had cooked the\
sandwich, wrapped it up in oiled paper, put it in a bag, brought it in,\
and the man had paid for it and gone out.\
\
\'93Bright boy can do everything,\'94 Max said. \'93He can cook and everything.\
You\'92d make some girl a nice wife, bright boy.\'94\
\
\'93Yes?\'94 George said. \'93Your friend, Ole Andreson, isn\'92t going to come.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll give him ten minutes,\'94 Max said.\
\
Max watched the mirror and the clock. The hands of the clock marked\
seven o\'92clock, and then five minutes past seven.\
\
\'93Come on, Al,\'94 said Max. \'93We better go. He\'92s not coming.\'94\
\
\'93Better give him five minutes,\'94 Al said from the kitchen.\
\
In the five minutes a man came in, and George explained that the cook\
was sick.\
\
\'93Why the hell don\'92t you get another cook?\'94 the man asked. \'93Aren\'92t you\
running a lunch-counter?\'94 He went out.\
\
\'93Come on, Al,\'94 Max said.\
\
\'93What about the two bright boys and the nigger?\'94\
\
\'93They\'92re all right.\'94\
\
\'93You think so?\'94\
\
\'93Sure. We\'92re through with it.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t like it,\'94 said Al. \'93It\'92s sloppy. You talk too much.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, what the hell,\'94 said Max. \'93We got to keep amused, haven\'92t we?\'94\
\
\'93You talk too much, all the same,\'94 Al said. He came out from the\
kitchen. The cut-off barrels of the shotgun made a slight bulge under\
the waist of his too tight-fitting overcoat. He straightened his coat\
with his gloved hands.\
\
\'93So long, bright boy,\'94 he said to George. \'93You got a lot of luck.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s the truth,\'94 Max said. \'93You ought to play the races, bright boy.\'94\
\
The two of them went out the door. George watched them, through the\
window, pass under the arc-light and cross the street. In their tight\
overcoats and derby hats they looked like a vaudeville team. George went\
back through the swinging-door into the kitchen and untied Nick and the\
cook.\
\
\'93I don\'92t want any more of that,\'94 said Sam, the cook. \'93I don\'92t want any\
more of that.\'94\
\
Nick stood up. He had never had a towel in his mouth before.\
\
\'93Say,\'94 he said. \'93What the hell?\'94 He was trying to swagger it off.\
\
\'93They were going to kill Ole Andreson,\'94 George said. \'93They were going to\
shoot him when he came in to eat.\'94\
\
\'93Ole Andreson?\'94\
\
\'93Sure.\'94\
\
The cook felt the corners of his mouth with his thumbs.\
\
\'93They all gone?\'94 he asked.\
\
\'93Yeah,\'94 said George. \'93They\'92re gone now.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t like it,\'94 said the cook. \'93I don\'92t like any of it at all.\'94\
\
\'93Listen,\'94 George said to Nick. \'93You better go see Ole Andreson.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93You better not have anything to do with it at all,\'94 Sam, the cook,\
said. \'93You better stay way out of it.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t go if you don\'92t want to,\'94 George said.\
\
\'93Mixing up in this ain\'92t going to get you anywhere,\'94 the cook said. \'93You\
stay out of it.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll go see him,\'94 Nick said to George. \'93Where does he live?\'94\
\
The cook turned away.\
\
\'93Little boys always know what they want to do,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93He lives up at Hirsch\'92s rooming-house,\'94 George said to Nick.\
\
\'93I\'92ll go up there.\'94\
\
Outside the arc-light shone through the bare branches of a tree. Nick\
walked up the street beside the car-tracks and turned at the next\
arc-light down a side-street. Three houses up the street was Hirsch\'92s\
rooming-house. Nick walked up the two steps and pushed the bell. A woman\
came to the door.\
\
\'93Is Ole Andreson here?\'94\
\
\'93Do you want to see him?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, if he\'92s in.\'94\
\
Nick followed the woman up a flight of stairs and back to the end of a\
corridor. She knocked on the door.\
\
\'93Who is it?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s somebody to see you, Mr. Andreson,\'94 the woman said.\
\
\'93It\'92s Nick Adams.\'94\
\
\'93Come in.\'94\
\
Nick opened the door and went into the room. Ole Andreson was lying on\
the bed with all his clothes on. He had been a heavyweight prizefighter\
and he was too long for the bed. He lay with his head on two pillows. He\
did not look at Nick.\
\
\'93What was it?\'94 he asked.\
\
\'93I was up at Henry\'92s,\'94 Nick said, \'93and two fellows came in and tied up\
me and the cook, and they said they were going to kill you.\'94\
\
It sounded silly when he said it. Ole Andreson said nothing.\
\
\'93They put us out in the kitchen,\'94 Nick went on. \'93They were going to\
shoot you when you came in to supper.\'94\
\
Ole Andreson looked at the wall and did not say anything.\
\
\'93George thought I better come and tell you about it.\'94\
\
\'93There isn\'92t anything I can do about it,\'94 Ole Andreson said.\
\
\'93I\'92ll tell you what they were like.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want to know what they were like,\'94 Ole Andreson said. He looked\
at the wall. \'93Thanks for coming to tell me about it.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s all right.\'94\
\
Nick looked at the big man lying on the bed.\
\
\'93Don\'92t you want me to go and see the police?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 Ole Andreson said. \'93That wouldn\'92t do any good.\'94\
\
\'93Isn\'92t there something I could do?\'94\
\
\'93No. There ain\'92t anything to do.\'94\
\
\'93Maybe it was just a bluff.\'94\
\
\'93No. It ain\'92t just a bluff.\'94\
\
Ole Andreson rolled over toward the wall.\
\
\'93The only thing is,\'94 he said, talking toward the wall, \'93I just can\'92t\
make up my mind to go out. I been in here all day.\'94\
\
\'93Couldn\'92t you get out of town?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 Ole Andreson said. \'93I\'92m through with all that running around.\'94\
\
He looked at the wall.\
\
\'93There ain\'92t anything to do now.\'94\
\
\'93Couldn\'92t you fix it up some way?\'94\
\
\'93No. I got in wrong.\'94 He talked in the same flat voice. \'93There ain\'92t\
anything to do. After a while I\'92ll make up my mind to go out.\'94\
\
\'93I better go back and see George,\'94 Nick said.\
\
\'93So long,\'94 said Ole Andreson. He did not look toward Nick. \'93Thanks for\
coming around.\'94\
\
Nick went out. As he shut the door he saw Ole Andreson with all his\
clothes on, lying on the bed looking at the wall.\
\
\'93He\'92s been in his room all day,\'94 the landlady said downstairs. \'93I guess\
he don\'92t feel well. I said to him: \'91Mr. Andreson, you ought to go out\
and take a walk on a nice fall day like this,\'92 but he didn\'92t feel like\
it.\'94\
\
\'93He doesn\'92t want to go out.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m sorry he don\'92t feel well,\'94 the woman said. \'93He\'92s an awfully nice\
man. He was in the ring, you know.\'94\
\
\'93I know it.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92d never know it except from the way his face is,\'94 the woman said.\
They stood talking just inside the street door. \'93He\'92s just as gentle.\'94\
\
