                            A MEAL IN SPEZIA\
\
We came into Spezia looking for a place to eat. The street was wide and\
the houses high and yellow. We followed the tram-track into the centre\
of town. On the walls of the houses were stencilled eye-bugging\
portraits of Mussolini, with hand-painted \'93vivas,\'94 the double V in black\
paint with drippings of paint down the wall. Side-streets went down to\
the harbor. It was bright and the people were all out for Sunday. The\
stone paving had been sprinkled and there were damp stretches in the\
dust. We went close to the curb to avoid a tram.\
\
\'93Let\'92s eat somewhere simple,\'94 Guy said.\
\
We stopped opposite two restaurant signs. We were standing across the\
street and I was buying the papers. The two restaurants were side by\
side. A woman standing in the doorway of one smiled at us and we crossed\
the street and went in.\
\
It was dark inside and at the back of the room three girls were sitting\
at a table with an old woman. Across from us, at another table, sat a\
sailor. He sat there neither eating nor drinking. Further back, a young\
man in a blue suit was writing at a table. His hair was pomaded and\
shining and he was very smartly dressed and clean-cut looking.\
\
The light came through the doorway, and through the window where\
vegetables, fruit, steaks, and chops were arranged in a show-case. A\
girl came and took our order and another girl stood in the doorway. We\
noticed that she wore nothing under her house dress. The girl who took\
our order put her arm around Guy\'92s neck while we were looking at the\
menu. There were three girls in all, and they all took turns going and\
standing in the doorway. The old woman at the table in the back of the\
room spoke to them and they sat down again with her.\
\
There was no doorway leading from the room except into the kitchen. A\
curtain hung over it. The girl who had taken our order came in from the\
kitchen with spaghetti. She put it on the table and brought a bottle of\
red wine and sat down at the table.\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I said to Guy, \'93you wanted to eat some place simple.\'94\
\
\'93This isn\'92t simple. This is complicated.\'94\
\
\'93What do you say?\'94 asked the girl. \'93Are you Germans?\'94\
\
\'93South Germans,\'94 I said. \'93The South Germans are a gentle, lovable\
people.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t understand,\'94 she said.\
\
\'93What\'92s the mechanics of this place?\'94 Guy asked. \'93Do I have to let her\
put her arm around my neck?\'94\
\
\'93Certainly,\'94 I said. \'93Mussolini has abolished the brothels. This is a\
restaurant.\'94\
\
The girl wore a one-piece dress. She leaned forward against the table\
and put her hands on her breasts and smiled. She smiled better on one\
side than on the other and turned the good side toward us. The charm of\
the good side had been enhanced by some event which had smoothed the\
other side of her nose in, as warm wax can be smoothed. Her nose,\
however, did not look like warm wax. It was very cold and firmed, only\
smoothed in. \'93You like me?\'94 she asked Guy.\
\
\'93He adores you,\'94 I said. \'93But he doesn\'92t speak Italian.\'94\
\
\'93Ich spreche Deutsch,\'94 she said, and stroked Guy\'92s hair.\
\
\'93Speak to the lady in your native tongue, Guy.\'94\
\
\'93Where do you come from?\'94 asked the lady.\
\
\'93Potsdam.\'94\
\
\'93And you will stay here now for a little while?\'94\
\
\'93In this so dear Spezia?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93Tell her we have to go,\'94 said Guy. \'93Tell her we are very ill, and have\
no money.\'94\
\
\'93My friend is a misogynist,\'94 I said, \'93an old German misogynist.\'94\
\
\'93Tell him I love him.\'94\
\
I told him.\
\
\'93Will you shut your mouth and get us out of here?\'94 Guy said. The lady\
had placed another arm around his neck. \'93Tell him he is mine,\'94 she said.\
I told him.\
\
\'93Will you get us out of here?\'94\
\
\'93You are quarrelling,\'94 the lady said. \'93You do not love one another.\'94\
\
\'93We are Germans,\'94 I said proudly, \'93old South Germans.\'94\
\
\'93Tell him he is a beautiful boy,\'94 the lady said. Guy is thirty-eight and\
takes some pride in the fact that he is taken for a travelling salesman\
in France. \'93You are a beautiful boy,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Who says so?\'94 Guy asked, \'93you or her?\'94\
\
\'93She does. I\'92m just your interpreter. Isn\'92t that what you got me in on\
this trip for?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m glad it\'92s her,\'94 said Guy. \'93I didn\'92t want to have to leave you here\
too.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. Spezia\'92s a lovely place.\'94\
\
\'93Spezia,\'94 the lady said. \'93You are talking about Spezia.\'94\
\
\'93Lovely place,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93It is my country,\'94 she said. \'93Spezia is my home and Italy is my\
country.\'94\
\
\'93She says that Italy is her country.\'94\
\
\'93Tell her it looks like her country,\'94 Guy said.\
\
\'93What have you for dessert?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93Fruit,\'94 she said. \'93We have bananas.\'94\
\
\'93Bananas are all right,\'94 Guy said. \'93They\'92ve got skins on.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, he takes bananas,\'94 the lady said. She embraced Guy.\
\
\'93What does she say?\'94 he asked, keeping his face out of the way.\
\
\'93She is pleased because you take bananas.\'94\
\
\'93Tell her I don\'92t take bananas.\'94\
\
\'93The Signor does not take bananas.\'94\
\
\'93Ah,\'94 said the lady, crestfallen, \'93he doesn\'92t take bananas.\'94\
\
\'93Tell her I take a cold bath every morning,\'94 Guy said.\
\
\'93The Signor takes a cold bath every morning.\'94\
\
\'93No understand,\'94 the lady said.\
\
Across from us, the property sailor had not moved. No one in the place\
paid any attention to him.\
\
\'93We want the bill,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Oh, no. You must stay.\'94\
\
\'93Listen,\'94 the clean-cut young man said from the table where he was\
writing, \'93let them go. These two are worth nothing.\'94\
\
The lady took my hand. \'93You won\'92t stay? You won\'92t ask him to stay?\'94\
\
\'93We have to go,\'94 I said. \'93We have to get to Pisa, or if possible,\
Firenze, to-night. We can amuse ourselves in those cities at the end of\
the day. It is now the day. In the day we must cover distance.\'94\
\
\'93To stay a little while is nice.\'94\
\
\'93To travel is necessary during the light of day.\'94\
\
\'93Listen,\'94 the clean-cut young man said. \'93Don\'92t bother to talk with these\
two. I tell you they are worth nothing and I know.\'94\
\
\'93Bring us the bill,\'94 I said. She brought the bill from the old woman and\
went back and sat at the table. Another girl came in from the kitchen.\
She walked the length of the room and stood in the doorway.\
\
\'93Don\'92t bother with these two,\'94 the clean-cut young man said in a wearied\
voice. \'93Come and eat. They are worth nothing.\'94\
\
We paid the bill and stood up. All the girls, the old woman, and the\
clean-cut young man sat down at table together. The property sailor sat\
with his head in his hands. No one had spoken to him all the time we\
were at lunch. The girl brought us our change that the old woman counted\
out for her and went back to her place at the table. We left a tip on\
the table and went out. When we were seated in the car ready to start,\
the girl came out and stood in the door. We started and I waved to her.\
She did not wave, but stood there looking after us.\
\
