\'93What do you mean?\'94\
\
\'93You better go back to town and stay there.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m sick of hearing you talk.\'94\
\
\'93Yes?\'94 says Soldier.\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 says Jack.\
\
\'93You\'92ll be a damn sight sicker when Walcott gets through with you.\'94\
\
\'93Sure,\'94 says Jack, \'93maybe I will. But I know I\'92m sick of you.\'94\
\
So Soldier went off on the train to town that same morning. I went down\
with him to the train. He was good and sore.\
\
\'93I was just kidding him,\'94 he said. We were waiting on the platform. \'93He\
can\'92t pull that stuff with me, Jerry.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s nervous and crabby,\'94 I said. \'93He\'92s a good fellow, Soldier.\'94\
\
\'93The hell he is. The hell he\'92s ever been a good fellow.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93so long, Soldier.\'94\
\
The train had come in. He climbed up with his bag.\
\
\'93So long, Jerry,\'94 he says. \'93You be in town before the fight?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t think so.\'94\
\
\'93See you then.\'94\
\
He went in and the conductor swung up and the train went out. I rode\
back to the farm in the cart. Jack was on the porch writing a letter to\
his wife. The mail had come and I got the papers and went over on the\
other side of the porch and sat down to read. Hogan came out the door\
and walked over to me.\
\
\'93Did he have a jam with Soldier?\'94\
\
\'93Not a jam,\'94 I said. \'93He just told him to go back to town.\'94\
\
\'93I could see it coming,\'94 Hogan said. \'93He never liked Soldier much.\'94\
\
\'93No. He don\'92t like many people.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s a pretty cold one,\'94 Hogan said.\
\
\'93Well, he\'92s always been fine to me.\'94\
\
\'93Me too,\'94 Hogan said. \'93I got no kick on him. He\'92s a cold one, though.\'94\
\
Hogan went in through the screen door and I sat there on the porch and\
read the papers. It was just starting to get fall weather and it\'92s nice\
country there in Jersey, up in the hills, and after I read the paper\
through I sat there and looked out at the country and the road down\
below against the woods with cars going along it, lifting the dust up.\
It was fine weather and pretty nice-looking country. Hogan came to the\
door and I said, \'93Say, Hogan, haven\'92t you got anything to shoot out\
here?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 Hogan said. \'93Only sparrows.\'94\
\
\'93Seen the paper?\'94 I said to Hogan.\
\
\'93What\'92s in it?\'94\
\
\'93Sande booted three of them in yesterday.\'94\
\
\'93I got that on the telephone last night.\'94\
\
\'93You follow them pretty close, Hogan?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93Oh, I keep in touch with them,\'94 Hogan said.\
\
\'93How about Jack?\'94 I says. \'93Does he still play them?\'94\
\
\'93Him?\'94 said Hogan. \'93Can you see him doing it?\'94\
\
Just then Jack came around the corner with the letter in his hand. He\'92s\
wearing a sweater and an old pair of pants and boxing shoes.\
\
\'93Got a stamp, Hogan?\'94 he asks.\
\
\'93Give me the letter,\'94 Hogan said. \'93I\'92ll mail it for you.\'94\
\
\'93Say, Jack,\'94 I said, \'93didn\'92t you used to play the ponies?\'94\
\
\'93Sure.\'94\
\
\'93I knew you did. I knew I used to see you out at Sheepshead.\'94\
\
\'93What did you lay off them for?\'94 Hogan asked.\
\
\'93Lost money.\'94\
\
Jack sat down on the porch by me. He leaned back against a post. He shut\
his eyes in the sun.\
\
\'93Want a chair?\'94 Hogan asked.\
\
\'93No,\'94 said Jack. \'93This is fine.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a nice day,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s pretty nice out in the country.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92d a damn sight rather be in town with the wife.\'94\
\
\'93Well, you only got another week.\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 Jack says. \'93That\'92s so.\'94\
\
We sat there on the porch. Hogan was inside at the office.\
\
\'93What do you think about the shape I\'92m in?\'94 Jack asked me.\
\
\'93Well, you can\'92t tell,\'94 I said. \'93You got a week to get around into\
form.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t stall me.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93you\'92re not right.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not sleeping,\'94 Jack said.\
\
\'93You\'92ll be all right in a couple of days.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 says Jack, \'93I got the insomnia.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s on your mind?\'94\
\
\'93I miss the wife.\'94\
\
\'93Have her come out.\'94\
\
\'93No. I\'92m too old for that.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll take a long walk before you turn in and get you good and tired.\'94\
\
\'93Tired!\'94 Jack says. \'93I\'92m tired all the time.\'94\
\
He was that way all week. He wouldn\'92t sleep at night and he\'92d get up in\
the morning feeling that way, you know, when you can\'92t shut your hands.\
\
\'93He\'92s stale as poorhouse cake,\'94 Hogan said. \'93He\'92s nothing.\'94\
\
\'93I never seen Walcott,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93He\'92ll kill him,\'94 said Hogan. \'93He\'92ll tear him in two.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93everybody\'92s got to get it sometime.\'94\
\
\'93Not like this, though,\'94 Hogan said. \'93They\'92ll think he never trained. It\
gives the farm a black eye.\'94\
\
\'93You hear what the reporters said about him?\'94\
\
\'93Didn\'92t I! They said he was awful. They said they oughtn\'92t to let him\
fight.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93they\'92re always wrong, ain\'92t they?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 said Hogan. \'93But this time they\'92re right.\'94\
\
\'93What the hell do they know about whether a man\'92s right or not?\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 said Hogan, \'93they\'92re not such fools.\'94\
\
\'93All they did was pick Willard at Toledo. This Lardner, he\'92s so wise\
now, ask him about when he picked Willard at Toledo.\'94\
\
\'93Aw, he wasn\'92t out,\'94 Hogan said. \'93He only writes the big fights.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t care who they are,\'94 I said. \'93What the hell do they know? They\
can write maybe, but what the hell do they know?\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t think Jack\'92s in any shape, do you?\'94 Hogan asked.\
\
\'93No. He\'92s through. All he needs is to have Corbett pick him to win for\
it to be all over.\'94\
\
\'93Well, Corbett\'92ll pick him,\'94 Hogan says.\
\
\'93Sure. He\'92ll pick him.\'94\
\
That night Jack didn\'92t sleep any either. The next morning was the last\
day before the fight. After breakfast we were out on the porch again.\
\
\'93What do you think about, Jack, when you can\'92t sleep?\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Oh, I worry,\'94 Jack says. \'93I worry about property I got up in the Bronx,\
I worry about property I got in Florida. I worry about the kids. I worry\
about the wife. Sometimes I think about fights. I think about that kike\
Ted Lewis and I get sore. I got some stocks and I worry about them. What\
the hell don\'92t I think about?\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93to-morrow night it\'92ll all be over.\'94\
\
\'93Sure,\'94 said Jack. \'93That always helps a lot, don\'92t it? That just fixes\
everything all up, I suppose. Sure.\'94\
\
He was sore all day. We didn\'92t do any work. Jack just moved around a\
little to loosen up. He shadow-boxed a few rounds. He didn\'92t even look\
good doing that. He skipped the rope a little while. He couldn\'92t sweat.\
\
\'93He\'92d be better not to do any work at all,\'94 Hogan said. We were standing\
watching him skip rope. \'93Don\'92t he ever sweat at all any more?\'94\
\
\'93He can\'92t sweat.\'94\
\
\'93Do you suppose he\'92s got the con? He never had any trouble making\
weight, did he?\'94\
\
\'93No, he hasn\'92t got any con. He just hasn\'92t got anything inside any\
more.\'94\
\
\'93He ought to sweat,\'94 said Hogan.\
\
Jack came over, skipping the rope. He was skipping up and down in front\
of us, forward and back, crossing his arms every third time.\
\
\'93Well,\'94 he says. \'93What are you buzzards talking about?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t think you ought to work any more,\'94 Hogan says. \'93You\'92ll be\
stale.\'94\
\
\'93Wouldn\'92t that be awful?\'94 Jack says and skips away down the floor,\
slapping the rope hard.\
\
That afternoon John Collins showed up out at the farm. Jack was up in\
his room. John, came out in a car from town. He had a couple of friends\
with him. The car stopped and they all got out.\
\
\'93Where\'92s Jack?\'94 John asked me.\
\
\'93Up in his room, lying down.\'94\
\
\'93Lying down?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93How is he?\'94\
\
I looked at the two fellows that were with John.\
\
\'93They\'92re friends of his,\'94 John said.\
\
\'93He\'92s pretty bad,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter with him?\'94\
\
\'93He don\'92t sleep.\'94\
\
\'93Hell,\'94 said John. \'93That Irishman could never sleep.\'94\
\
\'93He isn\'92t right,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Hell,\'94 John said. \'93He\'92s never right. I\'92ve had him for ten years and\
he\'92s never been right yet.\'94\
\
The fellows who were with him laughed.\
\
\'93I want you to shake hands with Mr. Morgan and Mr. Steinfelt,\'94 John\
said. \'93This is Mr. Doyle. He\'92s been training Jack.\'94\
\
\'93Glad to meet you,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Let\'92s go up and see the boy,\'94 the fellow called Morgan said.\
\
\'93Let\'92s have a look at him,\'94 Steinfelt said.\
\
We all went upstairs.\
\
\'93Where\'92s Hogan?\'94 John asked.\
\
\'93He\'92s out in the barn with a couple of his customers,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93He got many people out here now?\'94 John asked.\
\
\'93Just two.\'94\
\
\'93Pretty quiet, ain\'92t it?\'94 Morgan said.\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s pretty quiet.\'94\
\
We were outside Jack\'92s room. John knocked on the door. There wasn\'92t any\
answer.\
\
\'93Maybe he\'92s asleep,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93What the hell\'92s he sleeping in the daytime for?\'94\
\
John turned the handle and we all went in. Jack was lying asleep on the\
bed. He was face down and his face was in the pillow. Both his arms were\
around the pillow.\
\
\'93Hey, Jack!\'94 John said to him.\
\
Jack\'92s head moved a little on the pillow. \'93Jack!\'94 John says, leaning\
over him. Jack just dug a little deeper in the pillow. John touched him\
on the shoulder. Jack sat up and looked at us. He hadn\'92t shaved and he\
was wearing an old sweater.\
\
\'93Christ! Why can\'92t you let me sleep?\'94 he says to John.\
\
\'93Don\'92t be sore,\'94 John says. \'93I didn\'92t mean to wake you up.\'94\
\
\'93Oh no,\'94 Jack says. \'93Of course not.\'94\
\
\'93You know Morgan and Steinfelt,\'94 John said.\
\
\'93Glad to see you,\'94 Jack says.\
\
\'93How do you feel, Jack,\'94 Morgan asks him.\
\
\'93Fine,\'94 Jack says. \'93How the hell would I feel?\'94\
\
\'93You look fine,\'94 Steinfelt says.\
\
\'93Yes, don\'92t I,\'94 says Jack. \'93Say,\'94 he says to John. \'93You\'92re my manager.\
You get a big enough cut. Why the hell don\'92t you come out here when the\
reporters was out! You want Jerry and me to talk to them?\'94\
\
\'93I had Lew fighting in Philadelphia,\'94 John said.\
\
\'93What the hell\'92s that to me?\'94 Jack says. \'93You\'92re my manager. You get a\
big enough cut, don\'92t you? You aren\'92t making me any money in\
Philadelphia, are you? Why the hell aren\'92t you out here when I ought to\
have you?\'94\
\
\'93Hogan was here.\'94\
\
\'93Hogan,\'94 Jack says. \'93Hogan\'92s as dumb as I am.\'94\
\
\'93Soldier Bathlett was out here wukking with you for a while, wasn\'92t he?\'94\
Steinfelt said to change the subject.\
\
\'93Yes, he was out here,\'94 Jack says. \'93He was out here all right.\'94\
\
\'93Say, Jerry,\'94 John said to me. \'93Would you go and find Hogan and tell him\
we want to see him in about half an hour?\'94\
\
\'93Sure,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Why the hell can\'92t he stick around?\'94 Jack says. \'93Stick around, Jerry.\'94\
\
Morgan and Steinfelt looked at each other.\
\
\'93Quiet down, Jack,\'94 John said to him.\
\
\'93I better go find Hogan,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93All right, if you want to go,\'94 Jack says. \'93None of these guys are going\
to send you away, though.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll go find Hogan,\'94 I said.\
\
Hogan was out in the gym in the barn. He had a couple of his health-farm\
patients with the gloves on. They neither one wanted to hit the other,\
for fear the other would come back and hit him.\
\
\'93That\'92ll do,\'94 Hogan said when he saw me come in. \'93You can stop the\
slaughter. You gentlemen take a shower and Bruce will rub you down.\'94\
\
They climbed out through the ropes and Hogan came over to me.\
\
\'93John Collins is out with a couple of friends to see Jack,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I saw them come up in the car.\'94\
\
\'93Who are the two fellows with John?\'94\
\
\'93They\'92re what you call wise boys,\'94 Hogan said. \'93Don\'92t you know them\
two?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93That\'92s Happy Steinfelt and Lew Morgan. They got a pool-room.\'94\
\
\'93I been away a long time,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Sure,\'94 said Hogan. \'93That Happy Steinfelt\'92s a big operator.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve heard his name,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93He\'92s a pretty smooth boy,\'94 Hogan said. \'93They\'92re a couple of\
sharpshooters.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I said. \'93They want to see us in half an hour.\'94\
\
\'93You mean they don\'92t want to see us until a half an hour?\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s it.\'94\
\
\'93Come on in the office,\'94 Hogan said. \'93To hell with those sharpshooters.\'94\
\
After about thirty minutes or so Hogan and I went upstairs. We knocked\
on Jack\'92s door. They were talking inside the room.\
\
\'93Wait a minute,\'94 somebody said.\
\
\'93To hell with that stuff,\'94 Hogan said. \'93When you want to see me I\'92m down\
in the office.\'94\
\
We heard the door unlock. Steinfelt opened it.\
\
\'93Come on in, Hogan,\'94 he says. \'93We\'92re all going to have a drink.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 says Hogan. \'93That\'92s something.\'94\
\
We went in. Jack was sitting on the bed. John and Morgan were sitting on\
a couple of chairs. Steinfelt was standing up.\
\
\'93You\'92re a pretty mysterious lot of boys,\'94 Hogan said.\
\
\'93Hello, Danny,\'94 John says.\
\
\'93Hello, Danny,\'94 Morgan says and shakes hands.\
\
Jack doesn\'92t say anything. He just sits there on the bed. He ain\'92t with\
the others. He\'92s all by himself. He was wearing an old blue jersey and\
pants and had on boxing shoes. He needed a shave. Steinfelt and Morgan\
were dressers. John was quite a dresser too. Jack sat there looking\
Irish and tough.\
\
Steinfelt brought out a bottle and Hogan brought in some glasses and\
everybody had a drink. Jack and I took one and the rest of them went on\
and had two or three each.\
\
\'93Better save some for your ride back,\'94 Hogan said.\
\
\'93Don\'92t you worry. We got plenty,\'94 Morgan said.\
\
Jack hadn\'92t drunk anything since the one drink. He was standing up and\
looking at them. Morgan was sitting on the bed where Jack had sat.\
\
\'93Have a drink, Jack,\'94 John said and handed him the glass and the bottle.\
\
\'93No,\'94 Jack said, \'93I never liked to go to these wakes.\'94\
\
They all laughed. Jack didn\'92t laugh.\
\
They were all feeling pretty good when they left. Jack stood on the\
porch when they got into the car. They waved to him.\
\
\'93So long,\'94 Jack said.\
\
We had supper. Jack didn\'92t say anything all during the meal except,\
\'93Will you pass me this?\'94 or \'93Will you pass me that?\'94 The two health-farm\
patients ate at the same table with us. They were pretty nice fellows.\
After we finished eating we went out on the porch. It was dark early.\
\
\'93Like to take a walk, Jerry?\'94 Jack asked.\
\
\'93Sure,\'94 I said.\
\
We put on our coats and started out. It was quite a way down to the main\
road and then we walked along the main road about a mile and a half.\
Cars kept going by and we would pull out to the side until they were\
past. Jack didn\'92t say anything. After we had stepped out into the bushes\
to let a big car go by Jack said, \'93To hell with this walking. Come on\
back to Hogan\'92s.\'94\
\
We went along a side road that cut up over the hill and cut across the\
fields back to Hogan\'92s. We could see the lights of the house up on the\
hill. We came around to the front of the house and there standing in the\
doorway was Hogan.\
\
\'93Have a good walk?\'94 Hogan asked.\
\
\'93Oh, fine,\'94 Jack said. \'93Listen, Hogan. Have you got any liquor?\'94\
\
\'93Sure,\'94 says Hogan. \'93What\'92s the idea?\'94\
\
\'93Send it up to the room,\'94 Jack says. \'93I\'92m going to sleep to-night.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re the doctor,\'94 Hogan says.\
\
\'93Come on up to the room, Jerry,\'94 Jack says.\
\
Upstairs Jack sat on the bed with his head in his hands.\
\
\'93Ain\'92t it a life?\'94 Jack says.\
\
Hogan brought in a quart of liquor and two glasses.\
\
\'93Want some ginger-ale?\'94\
\
\'93What do you think I want to do, get sick?\'94\
\
\'93I just asked you,\'94 said Hogan.\
\
\'93Have a drink?\'94 said Jack.\
\
\'93No, thanks,\'94 said Hogan. He went out.\
\
\'93How about you, Jerry?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll have one with you,\'94 I said.\
\
Jack poured out a couple of drinks. \'93Now,\'94 he said, \'93I want to take it\
slow and easy.\'94\
\
\'93Put some water in it,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 Jack said. \'93I guess that\'92s better.\'94\
\
We had a couple of drinks without saying anything. Jack started to pour\
me another.\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said, \'93that\'92s all I want.\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 Jack said. He poured himself out another big shot and put\
water in it. He was lighting up a little.\
\
\'93That was a fine bunch out here this afternoon,\'94 he said. \'93They don\'92t\
take any chances, those two.\'94\
\
Then a little later, \'93Well,\'94 he says, \'93they\'92re right. What the hell\'92s\
the good in taking chances?\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you want another, Jerry?\'94 he said. \'93Come on, drink along with\
me.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t need it, Jack,\'94 I said. \'93I feel all right.\'94\
\
\'93Just have one more,\'94 Jack said. It was softening him up.\
\
\'93All right,\'94 I said.\
\
Jack poured one for me and another big one for himself.\
\
\'93You know,\'94 he said, \'93I like liquor pretty well. If I hadn\'92t been boxing\
I would have drunk quite a lot.\'94\
\
\'93Sure,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93You know,\'94 he said, \'93I missed a lot, boxing.\'94\
\
\'93You made plenty of money.\'94\
\
\'93Sure, that\'92s what I\'92m after. You know I miss a lot, Jerry.\'94\
\
\'93How do you mean?\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 he says, \'93like about the wife. And being away from home so much.\
It don\'92t do my girls any good. \'91Whose your old man?\'92 some of those\
society kids\'92ll say to them. \'91My old man\'92s Jack Brennan.\'92 That don\'92t do\
them any good.\'94\
\
\'93Hell,\'94 I said, \'93all that makes a difference is if they got dough.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 says Jack, \'93I got the dough for them all right.\'94\
\
He poured out another drink. The bottle was about empty.\
\
\'93Put some water in it,\'94 I said. Jack poured in some water.\
\
\'93You know,\'94 he says, \'93you ain\'92t got any idea how I miss the wife.\'94\
\
\'93Sure.\'94\
\
\'93You ain\'92t got any idea. You can\'92t have an idea what it\'92s like.\'94\
\
\'93It ought to be better out in the country than in town.\'94\
\
\'93With me now,\'94 Jack said, \'93it don\'92t make any difference where I am. You\
can\'92t have an idea what it\'92s like.\'94\
\
\'93Have another drink.\'94\
\
\'93Am I getting soused? Do I talk funny?\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re coming on all right.\'94\
\
\'93You can\'92t have an idea what it\'92s like. They ain\'92t anybody can have an\
idea what it\'92s like.\'94\
\
\'93Except the wife,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93She knows,\'94 Jack said. \'93She knows all right. She knows. You bet she\
knows.\'94\
\
\'93Put some water in that,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Jerry,\'94 says Jack, \'93you can\'92t have an idea what it gets to be like.\'94\
\
He was good and drunk. He was looking at me steady. His eyes were sort\
of too steady.\
\
\'93You\'92ll sleep all right,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Listen, Jerry,\'94 Jack says. \'93You want to make some money? Get some money\
down on Walcott.\'94\
\
\'93Yes?\'94\
\
\'93Listen, Jerry,\'94 Jack put down the glass. \'93I\'92m not drunk now, see? You\
know what I\'92m betting on him? Fifty grand.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s a lot of dough.\'94\
\
\'93Fifty grand,\'94 Jack says, \'93at two to one. I\'92ll get twenty-five thousand\
bucks. Get some money on him, Jerry.\'94\
\
\'93It sounds good,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93How can I beat him?\'94 Jack says. \'93It ain\'92t crooked. How can I beat him?\
Why not make money on it?\'94\
\
\'93Put some water in that,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I\'92m through after this fight,\'94 Jack says. \'93I\'92m through with it. I got\
to take a beating. Why shouldn\'92t I make money on it?\'94\
\
\'93Sure.\'94\
\
\'93I ain\'92t slept for a week,\'94 Jack says. \'93All night I lay awake and worry\
my can off. I can\'92t sleep, Jerry. You ain\'92t got an idea what it\'92s like\
when you can\'92t sleep.\'94\
\
\'93Sure.\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t sleep. That\'92s all. I just can\'92t sleep. What\'92s the use of taking\
care of yourself all these years when you can\'92t sleep?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s bad.\'94\
\
\'93You ain\'92t got an idea what it\'92s like, Jerry, when you can\'92t sleep.\'94\
\
\'93Put some water in that,\'94 I said.\
\
Well, about eleven o\'92clock Jack passes out and I put him to bed. Finally\
he\'92s so he can\'92t keep from sleeping. I helped him get his clothes off\
and got him into bed.\
\
\'93You\'92ll sleep all right, Jack,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Sure,\'94 Jack says, \'93I\'92ll sleep now.\'94\
\
\'93Good-night, Jack,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Good-night, Jerry,\'94 Jack says. \'93You\'92re the only friend I got.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, hell,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93You\'92re the only friend I got,\'94 Jack says, \'93the only friend I got.\'94\
\
\'93Go to sleep,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I\'92ll sleep,\'94 Jack says.\
\
Downstairs Hogan was sitting at the desk in the office reading the\
papers. He looked up. \'93Well, you get your boy friend to sleep?\'94 he asks.\
\
\'93He\'92s off.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s better for him than not sleeping,\'94 Hogan said.\
\
\'93Sure.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92d have a hell of a time explaining that to these sport writers\
though,\'94 Hogan said.\
\
\'93Well, I\'92m going to bed myself,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Good-night,\'94 said Hogan.\
\
In the morning I came downstairs about eight o\'92clock and got some\
breakfast. Hogan had his two customers out in the barn doing exercises.\
I went out and watched them.\
\
\'93One! Two! Three! Four!\'94 Hogan was counting for them. \'93Hello, Jerry,\'94 he\
said. \'93Is Jack up yet?\'94\
\
\'93No. He\'92s still sleeping.\'94\
\
I went back to my room and packed up to go in to town. About nine-thirty\
I heard Jack getting up in the next room. When I heard him go downstairs\
I went down after him. Jack was sitting at the breakfast table. Hogan\
had come in and was standing beside the table.\
\
\'93How do you feel, Jack?\'94 I asked him.\
\
\'93Not so bad.\'94\
\
\'93Sleep well?\'94 Hogan asked.\
\
\'93I slept all right,\'94 Jack said. \'93I got a thick tongue but I ain\'92t got a\
head.\'94\
\
\'93Good,\'94 said Hogan. \'93That was good liquor.\'94\
\
\'93Put it on the bill,\'94 Jack says.\
\
\'93What time you want to go into town?\'94 Hogan asked.\
\
\'93Before lunch,\'94 Jack says. \'93The eleven o\'92clock train.\'94\
\
\'93Sit down, Jerry,\'94 Jack said. Hogan went out.\
\
I sat down at the table. Jack was eating a grape-fruit. When he\'92d find a\
seed he\'92d spit it out in the spoon and dump it on the plate.\
\
\'93I guess I was pretty stewed last night,\'94 he started.\
\
\'93You drank some liquor.\'94\
\
\'93I guess I said a lot of fool things.\'94\
\
\'93You weren\'92t bad.\'94\
\
\'93Where\'92s Hogan?\'94 he asked. He was through with the grape-fruit.\
\
\'93He\'92s out in front in the office.\'94\
\
\'93What did I say about betting on the fight?\'94 Jack asked. He was holding\
the spoon and sort of poking at the grape-fruit with it.\
\
The girl came in with some ham and eggs and took away the grape-fruit.\
\
\'93Bring me another glass of milk,\'94 Jack said to her. She went out.\
\
\'93You said you had fifty grand on Walcott,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93That\'92s right,\'94 Jack said.\
\
\'93That\'92s a lot of money.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t feel too good about it,\'94 Jack said.\
\
\'93Something might happen.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 Jack said. \'93He wants the title bad. They\'92ll be shooting with him\
all right.\'94\
\
\'93You can\'92t ever tell.\'94\
\
\'93No. He wants the title. It\'92s worth a lot of money to him.\'94\
\
\'93Fifty grand is a lot of money,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93It\'92s business,\'94 said Jack. \'93I can\'92t win. You know I can\'92t win anyway.\'94\
\
\'93As long as you\'92re in there you got a chance.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 Jack says. \'93I\'92m all through. It\'92s just business.\'94\
\
\'93How do you feel?\'94\
\
\'93Pretty good,\'94 Jack said. \'93The sleep was what I needed.\'94\
\
\'93You might go good.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll give them a good show,\'94 Jack said.\
\
After breakfast Jack called up his wife on the long-distance. He was\
inside the booth telephoning.\
\
\'93That\'92s the first time he\'92s called her up since he\'92s out here,\'94 Hogan\
said.\
\
\'93He writes her every day.\'94\
\
\'93Sure,\'94 Hogan says, \'93a letter only costs two cents.\'94\
\
Hogan said good-by to us and Bruce, the nigger rubber, drove us down to\
the train in the cart.\
\
\'93Good-by, Mr. Brennan,\'94 Bruce said at the train, \'93I sure hope you knock\
his can off.\'94\
\
\'93So long,\'94 Jack said. He gave Bruce two dollars. Bruce had worked on him\
a lot. He looked kind of disappointed. Jack saw me looking at Bruce\
holding the two dollars.\
\
\'93It\'92s all in the bill,\'94 he said. \'93Hogan charged me for the rubbing.\'94\
\
On the train going into town Jack didn\'92t talk. He sat in the corner of\
the seat with his ticket in his hat-band and looked out of the window.\
Once he turned and spoke to me.\
\
\'93I told the wife I\'92d take a room at the Shelby to-night,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s\
just around the corner from the Garden. I can go up to the house\
to-morrow morning.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s a good idea,\'94 I said. \'93Your wife ever see you fight, Jack?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 Jack says. \'93She never seen me fight.\'94\
\
I thought he must be figuring on taking an awful beating if he doesn\'92t\
want to go home afterward. In town we took a taxi up to the Shelby. A\
boy came out and took our bags and we went in to the desk.\
\
\'93How much are the rooms?\'94 Jack asked.\
\
\'93We only have double rooms,\'94 the clerk says. \'93I can give you a nice\
double room for ten dollars.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s too steep.\'94\
\
\'93I can give you a double room for seven dollars.\'94\
\
\'93With a bath?\'94\
\
\'93Certainly.\'94\
\
\'93You might as well bunk with me, Jerry,\'94 Jack says.\
\
\'93Oh,\'94 I said, \'93I\'92ll sleep down at my brother-in-law\'92s.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t mean for you to pay it,\'94 Jack says. \'93I just want to get my\
money\'92s worth.\'94\
\
\'93Will you register, please?\'94 the clerk says. He looked at the names.\
\'93Number 238, Mister Brennan.\'94\
\
We went up in the elevator. It was a nice big room with two beds and a\
door opening into a bath-room.\
\
\'93This is pretty good,\'94 Jack says.\
\
The boy who brought us up pulled up the curtains and brought in our\
bags. Jack didn\'92t make any move, so I gave the boy a quarter. We washed\
up and Jack said we better go out and get something to eat.\
\
We ate a lunch at Jimmey Handley\'92s place. Quite a lot of the boys were\
there. When we were about half through eating, John came in and sat down\
with us. Jack didn\'92t talk much.\
\
\'93How are you on the weight, Jack?\'94 John asked him. Jack was putting away\
a pretty good lunch.\
\
\'93I could make it with my clothes on,\'94 Jack said. He never had to worry\
about taking off weight. He was a natural welter-weight and he\'92d never\
gotten fat. He\'92d lost weight out at Hogan\'92s.\
\
\'93Well, that\'92s one thing you never had to worry about,\'94 John said.\
\
\'93That\'92s one thing,\'94 Jack says.\
\
We went around to the garden to weigh in after lunch. The match was made\
at a hundred forty-seven pounds at three o\'92clock. Jack stepped on the\
scales with a towel around him. The bar didn\'92t move. Walcott had just\
weighed and was standing with a lot of people around him.\
\
\'93Let\'92s see what you weigh, Jack,\'94 Freedman, Walcott\'92s manager said.\
\
\'93All right, weigh _him_ then,\'94 Jack jerked his head toward Walcott.\
\
\'93Drop the towel,\'94 Freedman said.\
\
\'93What do you make it?\'94 Jack asked the fellows who were weighing.\
\
\'93One hundred and forty-three pounds,\'94 the fat man who was weighing said.\
\
\'93You\'92re down fine, Jack,\'94 Freedman says.\
\
\'93Weigh _him_,\'94 Jack says.\
\
Walcott came over. He was a blond with wide shoulders and arms like a\
heavyweight. He didn\'92t have much legs. Jack stood about half a head\
taller than he did.\
\
\'93Hello, Jack,\'94 he said. His face was plenty marked up.\
\
\'93Hello,\'94 said Jack. \'93How you feel?\'94\
\
\'93Good,\'94 Walcott says. He dropped the towel from around his waist and\
stood on the scales. He had the widest shoulders and back you ever saw.\
\
\'93One hundred and forty-six pounds and twelve ounces.\'94\
\
Walcott stepped off and grinned at Jack.\
\
\'93Well,\'94 John says to him, \'93Jack\'92s spotting you about four pounds.\'94\
\
\'93More than that when I come in, kid,\'94 Walcott says. \'93I\'92m going to go and\
eat now.\'94\
\
We went back and Jack got dressed. \'93He\'92s a pretty tough-looking boy,\'94\
Jack says to me.\
\
\'93He looks as though he\'92d been hit plenty of times.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes,\'94 Jack says. \'93He ain\'92t hard to hit.\'94\
\
\'93Where are you going?\'94 John asked when Jack was dressed.\
\
\'93Back to the hotel,\'94 Jack says. \'93You looked after everything?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 John says. \'93It\'92s all looked after.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m going to lie down a while,\'94 Jack says.\
\
\'93I\'92ll come around for you about a quarter to seven and we\'92ll go and\
eat.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
Up at the hotel Jack took off his shoes and his coat and lay down for a\
while. I wrote a letter. I looked over a couple of times and Jack wasn\'92t\
sleeping. He was lying perfectly still but every once in a while his\
eyes would open. Finally he sits up.\
\
\'93Want to play some cribbage, Jerry?\'94 he says.\
\
\'93Sure,\'94 I said.\
\
He went over to his suitcase and got out the cards and the cribbage\
board. We played cribbage and he won three dollars off me. John knocked\
at the door and came in.\
\
\'93Want to play some cribbage, John?\'94 Jack asked him.\
\
John put his kelly down on the table. It was all wet. His coat was wet\
too.\
\
\'93Is it raining?\'94 Jack asks.\
\
\'93It\'92s pouring,\'94 John says. \'93The taxi I had, got tied up in the traffic\
and I got out and walked.\'94\
\
\'93Come on, play some cribbage,\'94 Jack says.\
\
\'93You ought to go and eat.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 says Jack. \'93I don\'92t want to eat yet.\'94\
\
So they played cribbage for about half an hour and Jack won a dollar and\
a half off him.\
\
\'93Well, I suppose we got to go eat,\'94 Jack says. He went to the window and\
looked out.\
\
\'93Is it still raining?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s eat in the hotel,\'94 John says.\
\
\'93All right,\'94 Jack says, \'93I\'92ll play you once more to see who pays for the\
meal.\'94\
\
After a little while Jack gets up and says, \'93You buy the meal, John,\'94\
and we went downstairs and ate in the big dining-room.\
\
After we ate we went upstairs and Jack played cribbage with John again\
and won two dollars and a half off him. Jack was feeling pretty good.\
John had a bag with him with all his stuff in it. Jack took off his\
shirt and collar and put on a jersey and a sweater, so he wouldn\'92t catch\
cold when he came out, and put his ring clothes and his bathrobe in a\
bag.\
\
\'93You all ready?\'94 John asks him. \'93I\'92ll call up and have them get a taxi.\'94\
\
Pretty soon the telephone rang and they said the taxi was waiting.\
\
We rode down in the elevator and went out through the lobby, and got in\
a taxi and rode around to the Garden. It was raining hard but there was\
a lot of people outside on the streets. The Garden was sold out. As we\
came in on our way to the dressing-room I saw how full it was. It looked\
like half a mile down to the ring. It was all dark. Just the lights over\
the ring.\
\
\'93It\'92s a good thing, with this rain, they didn\'92t try and pull this fight\
in the ball park,\'94 John said.\
\
\'93They got a good crowd,\'94 Jack says.\
\
\'93This is a fight that would draw a lot more than the Garden could hold.\'94\
\
\'93You can\'92t tell about the weather,\'94 Jack says.\
\
John came to the door of the dressing-room and poked his head in. Jack\
was sitting there with his bathrobe on, he had his arms folded and was\
looking at the floor. John had a couple of handlers with him. They\
looked over his shoulder. Jack looked up.\
\
\'93Is he in?\'94 he asked.\
\
\'93He\'92s just gone down,\'94 John said.\
\
We started down. Walcott was just getting into the ring. The crowd gave\
him a big hand. He climbed through between the ropes and put his two\
fists together and smiled, and shook them at the crowd, first at one\
side of the ring, then at the other, and then sat down. Jack got a good\
hand coming down through the crowd. Jack is Irish and the Irish always\
get a pretty good hand. An Irishman don\'92t draw in New York like a Jew or\
an Italian but they always get a good hand. Jack climbed up and bent\
down to go through the ropes and Walcott came over from his corner and\
pushed the rope down for Jack to go through. The crowd thought that was\
wonderful. Walcott put his hand on Jack\'92s shoulder and they stood there\
just for a second.\
\
\'93So you\'92re going to be one of these popular champions,\'94 Jack says to\
him. \'93Take your goddam hand off my shoulder.\'94\
\
\'93Be yourself,\'94 Walcott says.\
\
This is all great for the crowd. How gentlemanly the boys are before the\
fight! How they wish each other luck!\
\
Solly Freedman came over to our corner while Jack is bandaging his hands\
and John is over in Walcott\'92s corner. Jack puts his thumb through the\
slit in the bandage and then wrapped his hand nice and smooth. I taped\
it around the wrist and twice across the knuckles.\
\
\'93Hey,\'94 Freedman says. \'93Where do you get all that tape?\'94\
\
\'93Feel of it,\'94 Jack says. \'93It\'92s soft, ain\'92t it? Don\'92t be a hick.\'94\
\
Freedman stands there all the time while Jack bandages the other hand,\
and one of the boys that\'92s going to handle him brings the gloves and I\
pull them on and work them around.\
\
\'93Say, Freedman,\'94 Jack asks, \'93what nationality is this Walcott?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Solly says. \'93He\'92s some sort of a Dane.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s a Bohemian,\'94 the lad who brought the gloves said.\
\
The referee called them out to the centre of the ring and Jack walks\
out. Walcott comes out smiling. They met and the referee put his arm on\
each of their shoulders.\
\
\'93Hello, popularity,\'94 Jack says to Walcott.\
\
\'93Be yourself.\'94\
\
\'93What do you call yourself \'91Walcott\'92 for?\'94 Jack says. \'93Didn\'92t you know\
he was a nigger?\'94\
\
\'93Listen\'97\'94 says the referee, and he gives them the same old line. Once\
Walcott interrupts him. He grabs Jack\'92s arm and says, \'93Can I hit when\
he\'92s got me like this?\'94\
\
\'93Keep your hands off me,\'94 Jack says. \'93There ain\'92t no moving-pictures of\
this.\'94\
\
They went back to their corners. I lifted the bathrobe off Jack and he\
leaned on the ropes and flexed his knees a couple of times and scuffed\
his shoes in the rosin. The gong rang and Jack turned quick and went\
out. Walcott came toward him and they touched gloves and as soon as\
Walcott dropped his hands Jack jumped his left into his face twice.\
There wasn\'92t anybody ever boxed better than Jack. Walcott was after him,\
going forward all the time with his chin on his chest. He\'92s a hooker and\
he carries his hands pretty low. All he knows is to get in there and\
sock. But every time he gets in there close, Jack has the left hand in\
his face. It\'92s just as though it\'92s automatic. Jack just raises the left\
hand up and it\'92s in Walcott\'92s face. Three or four times Jack brings the\
right over but Walcott gets it on the shoulder or high up on the head.\
He\'92s just like all these hookers. The only thing he\'92s afraid of is\
another one of the same kind. He\'92s covered everywhere you can hurt him.\
He don\'92t care about a left-hand in his face.\
\
After about four rounds Jack has him bleeding bad and his face all cut\
up, but every time Walcott\'92s got in close he\'92s socked so hard he\'92s got\
two big red patches on both sides just below Jack\'92s ribs. Every time he\
gets in close, Jack ties him up, then gets one hand loose and uppercuts\
him, but when Walcott gets his hands loose he socks Jack in the body so\
they can hear it outside in the street. He\'92s a socker.\
\
It goes along like that for three rounds more. They don\'92t talk any.\
They\'92re working all the time. We worked over Jack plenty too, in between\
the rounds. He don\'92t look good at all but he never does much work in the\
ring. He don\'92t move around much and that left-hand is just automatic.\
It\'92s just like it was connected with Walcott\'92s face and Jack just had to\
wish it in every time. Jack is always calm in close and he doesn\'92t waste\
any juice. He knows everything about working in close too and he\'92s\
getting away with a lot of stuff. While they were in our corner I\
watched him tie Walcott up, get his right hand loose, turn it and come\
up with an uppercut that got Walcott\'92s nose with the heel of the glove.\
Walcott was bleeding bad and leaned his nose on Jack\'92s shoulder so as to\
give Jack some of it too, and Jack sort of lifted his shoulder sharp and\
caught him against the nose, and then brought down the right hand and\
did the same thing again.\
\
Walcott was sore as hell. By the time they\'92d gone five rounds he hated\
Jack\'92s guts. Jack wasn\'92t sore; that is, he wasn\'92t any sorer than he\
always was. He certainly did used to make the fellows he fought hate\
boxing. That was why he hated Kid Lewis so. He never got the Kid\'92s goat.\
Kid Lewis always had about three new dirty things Jack couldn\'92t do. Jack\
was as safe as a church all the time he was in there, as long as he was\
strong. He certainly was treating Walcott rough. The funny thing was it\
looked as though Jack was an open classic boxer. That was because he had\
all that stuff too.\
\
After the seventh round Jack says, \'93My left\'92s getting heavy.\'94\
\
From then he started to take a beating. It didn\'92t show at first. But\
instead of him running the fight it was Walcott was running it, instead\
of being safe all the time now he was in trouble. He couldn\'92t keep him\
out with the left hand now. It looked as though it was the same as ever,\
only now instead of Walcott\'92s punches just missing him they were just\
hitting him. He took an awful beating in the body.\
\
\'93What\'92s the round?\'94 Jack asked.\
\
\'93The eleventh.\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t stay,\'94 Jack says. \'93My legs are going bad.\'94\
\
Walcott had been just hitting him for a long time. It was like a\
baseball catcher pulls the ball and takes some of the shock off. From\
now on Walcott commenced to land solid. He certainly was a\
socking-machine. Jack was just trying to block everything now. It didn\'92t\
show what an awful beating he was taking. In between the rounds I worked\
on his legs. The muscles would flutter under my hands all the time I was\
rubbing them. He was sick as hell.\
\
\'93How\'92s it go?\'94 he asked John, turning around, his face all swollen.\
\
\'93It\'92s his fight.\'94\
\
\'93I think I can last,\'94 Jack says. \'93I don\'92t want this bohunk to stop me.\'94\
\
It was going just the way he thought it would. He knew he couldn\'92t beat\
Walcott. He wasn\'92t strong any more. He was all right though. His money\
was all right and now he wanted to finish it off right to please\
himself. He didn\'92t want to be knocked out.\
\
The gong rang and we pushed him out. He went out slow. Walcott came\
right out after him. Jack put the left in his face and Walcott took it,\
came in under it and started working on Jack\'92s body. Jack tried to tie\
him up and it was just like trying to hold on to a buzz-saw. Jack broke\
away from it and missed with the right. Walcott clipped him with a\
left-hook and Jack went down. He went down on his hands and knees and\
looked at us. The referee started counting. Jack was watching us and\
shaking his head. At eight John motioned to him. You couldn\'92t hear on\
account of the crowd. Jack got up. The referee had been holding Walcott\
back with one arm while he counted.\
\
When Jack was on his feet Walcott started toward him.\
\
\'93Watch yourself, Jimmy,\'94 I heard Solly Freedman yell to him.\
\
Walcott came up to Jack looking at him. Jack stuck the left hand at him.\
Walcott just shook his head. He backed Jack up against the ropes,\
measured him and then hooked the left very light to the side of Jack\'92s\
head and socked the right into the body as hard as he could sock, just\
as low as he could get it. He must have hit him five inches below the\
belt. I thought the eyes would come out of Jack\'92s head. They stuck way\
out. His mouth come open.\
\
The referee grabbed Walcott. Jack stepped forward. If he went down there\
went fifty thousand bucks. He walked as though all his insides were\
going to fall out.\
\
\'93It wasn\'92t low,\'94 he said. \'93It was a accident.\'94\
\
The crowd were yelling so you couldn\'92t hear anything.\
\
\'93I\'92m all right,\'94 Jack says. They were right in front of us. The referee\
looks at John and then he shakes his head.\
\
\'93Come on, you polak son-of-a-bitch,\'94 Jack says to Walcott.\
\
John was hanging onto the ropes. He had the towel ready to chuck in.\
Jack was standing just a little way out from the ropes. He took a step\
forward. I saw the sweat come out on his face like somebody had squeezed\
it and a big drop went down his nose.\
\
\'93Come on and fight,\'94 Jack says to Walcott.\
\
The referee looked at John and waved Walcott on.\
\
\'93Go in there, you slob,\'94 he says.\
\
Walcott went in. He didn\'92t know what to do either. He never thought Jack\
could have stood it. Jack put the left in his face. There was such a\
hell of a lot of yelling going on. They were right in front of us.\
Walcott hit him twice. Jack\'92s face was the worst thing I ever saw,\'97the\
look on it! He was holding himself and all his body together and it all\
showed on his face. All the time he was thinking and holding his body in\
where it was busted.\
\
Then he started to sock. His face looked awful all the time. He started\
to sock with his hands low down by his side, swinging at Walcott.\
Walcott covered up and Jack was swinging wild at Walcott\'92s head. Then he\
swung the left and it hit Walcott in the groin and the right hit Walcott\
right bang where he\'92d hit Jack. Way low below the belt. Walcott went\
down and grabbed himself there and rolled and twisted around.\
\
The referee grabbed Jack and pushed him toward his corner. John jumps\
into the ring. There was all this yelling going on. The referee was\
talking with the judges and then the announcer got into the ring with\
the megaphone and says, \'93Walcott on a foul.\'94\
\
The referee is talking to John and he says, \'93What could I do? Jack\
wouldn\'92t take the foul. Then when he\'92s groggy he fouls him.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92d lost it anyway,\'94 John says.\
\
Jack\'92s sitting on the chair. I\'92ve got his gloves off and he\'92s holding\
himself in down there with both hands. When he\'92s got something\
supporting it his face doesn\'92t look so bad.\
\
\'93Go over and say you\'92re sorry,\'94 John says into his ear. \'93It\'92ll look\
good.\'94\
\
Jack stands up and the sweat comes out all over his face. I put the\
bathrobe around him and he holds himself in with one hand under the\
bathrobe and goes across the ring. They\'92ve picked Walcott up and they\'92re\
working on him. There\'92re a lot of people in Walcott\'92s corner. Nobody\
speaks to Jack. He leans over Walcott.\
\
\'93I\'92m sorry,\'94 Jack says. \'93I didn\'92t mean to foul you.\'94\
\
Walcott doesn\'92t say anything. He looks too damned sick.\
\
\'93Well, you\'92re the champion now,\'94 Jack says to him. \'93I hope you get a\
hell of a lot of fun out of it.\'94\
\
\'93Leave the kid alone,\'94 Solly Freedman says.\
\
\'93Hello, Solly,\'94 Jack says. \'93I\'92m sorry I fouled your boy.\'94\
\
Freedman just looks at him.\
\
Jack went to his corner walking that funny jerky way and we got him down\
through the ropes and through the reporters\'92 tables and out down the\
aisle. A lot of people want to slap Jack on the back. He goes out\
through all that mob in his bathrobe to the dressing-room. It\'92s a\
popular win for Walcott. That\'92s the way the money was bet in the Garden.\
\
Once we got inside the dressing-room Jack lay down and shut his eyes.\
\
\'93We want to get to the hotel and get a doctor,\'94 John says.\
\
\'93I\'92m all busted inside,\'94 Jack says.\
\
\'93I\'92m sorry as hell, Jack,\'94 John says.\
\
\'93It\'92s all right,\'94 Jack says.\
\
He lies there with his eyes shut.\
\
\'93They certainly tried a nice double-cross,\'94 John said.\
\
\'93Your friends Morgan and Steinfelt,\'94 Jack said. \'93You got nice friends.\'94\
\
He lies there, his eyes are open now. His face has still got that awful\
drawn look.\
\
\'93It\'92s funny how fast you can think when it means that much money,\'94 Jack\
says.\
\
\'93You\'92re some boy, Jack,\'94 John says.\
\
\'93No,\'94 Jack says. \'93It was nothing.\'94\
\
\
\
