                              TEN INDIANS\
\
\
AFTER one Fourth of July, Nick, driving home late from town in the big\
wagon with Joe Garner and his family, passed nine drunken Indians along\
the road. He remembered there were nine because Joe Garner, driving\
along in the dusk, pulled up the horses, jumped down into the road and\
dragged an Indian out of the wheel rut. The Indian had been asleep, face\
down in the sand. Joe dragged him into the bushes and got back up on the\
wagon-box.\
\
\'93That makes nine of them,\'94 Joe said, \'93just between here and the edge of\
town.\'94\
\
\'93Them Indians,\'94 said Mrs. Garner.\
\
Nick was on the back seat with the two Garner boys. He was looking out\
from the back seat to see the Indian where Joe had dragged him alongside\
of the road.\
\
\'93Was it Billy Tabeshaw?\'94 Carl asked.\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93His pants looked mighty like Billy.\'94\
\
\'93All Indians wear the same kind of pants.\'94\
\
\'93I didn\'92t see him at all,\'94 Frank said. \'93Pa was down into the road and\
back up again before I seen a thing. I thought he was killing a snake.\'94\
\
\'93Plenty of Indians\'92ll kill snakes to-night, I guess,\'94 Joe Garner said.\
\
\'93Them Indians,\'94 said Mrs. Garner.\
\
They drove along. The road turned off from the main highway and went up\
into the hills. It was hard pulling for the horses and the boys got down\
and walked. The road was sandy. Nick looked back from the top of the\
hill by the schoolhouse. He saw the lights of Petoskey and, off across\
Little Traverse Bay, the lights of Harbour Springs. They climbed back in\
the wagon again.\
\
\'93They ought to put some gravel on that stretch,\'94 Joe Garner said. The\
wagon went along the road through the woods. Joe and Mrs. Garner sat\
close together on the front seat. Nick sat between the two boys. The\
road came out into a clearing.\
\
\'93Right here was where Pa ran over the skunk.\'94\
\
\'93It was further on.\'94\
\
\'93It don\'92t make no difference where it was,\'94 Joe said without turning his\
head. \'93One place is just as good as another to run over a skunk.\'94\
\
\'93I saw two skunks last night,\'94 Nick said.\
\
\'93Where?\'94\
\
\'93Down by the lake. They were looking for dead fish along the beach.\'94\
\
\'93They were coons probably,\'94 Carl said.\
\
\'93They were skunks. I guess I know skunks.\'94\
\
\'93You ought to,\'94 Carl said. \'93You got an Indian girl.\'94\
\
\'93Stop talking that way, Carl,\'94 said Mrs. Garner.\
\
\'93Well, they smell about the same.\'94\
\
Joe Garner laughed.\
\
\'93You stop laughing, Joe,\'94 Mrs. Garner said. \'93I won\'92t have Carl talk that\
way.\'94\
\
\'93Have you got an Indian girl, Nickie?\'94 Joe asked.\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93He has too, Pa,\'94 Frank said. \'93Prudence Mitchell\'92s his girl.\'94\
\
\'93She\'92s not.\'94\
\
\'93He goes to see her every day.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t.\'94 Nick, sitting between the two boys in the dark, felt hollow\
and happy inside himself to be teased about Prudence Mitchell. \'93She\
ain\'92t my girl,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93Listen to him,\'94 said Carl. \'93I see them together every day.\'94\
\
\'93Carl can\'92t get a girl,\'94 his mother said, \'93not even a squaw.\'94\
\
Carl was quiet.\
\
\'93Carl ain\'92t no good with girls,\'94 Frank said.\
\
\'93You shut up.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re all right, Carl,\'94 Joe Garner said. \'93Girls never got a man\
anywhere. Look at your pa.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, that\'92s what you would say,\'94 Mrs. Garner moved close to Joe as the\
wagon jolted. \'93Well, you had plenty of girls in your time.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll bet Pa wouldn\'92t ever have had a squaw for a girl.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you think it,\'94 Joe said. \'93You better watch out to keep Prudie,\
Nick.\'94\
\
His wife whispered to him and Joe laughed.\
\
\'93What you laughing at?\'94 asked Frank.\
\
\'93Don\'92t you say it, Garner,\'94 his wife warned. Joe laughed again.\
\
\'93Nickie can have Prudence,\'94 Joe Garner said. \'93I got a good girl.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s the way to talk,\'94 Mrs. Garner said.\
\
The horses were pulling heavily in the sand. Joe reached out in the dark\
with the whip.\
\
\'93Come on, pull into it. You\'92ll have to pull harder than this to-morrow.\'94\
\
They trotted down the long hill, the wagon jolting. At the farmhouse\
everybody got down. Mrs. Garner unlocked the door, went inside, and came\
out with a lamp in her hand. Carl and Nick unloaded the things from the\
back of the wagon. Frank sat on the front seat to drive to the barn and\
put up the horses. Nick went up the steps and opened the kitchen door.\
Mrs. Garner was building a fire in the stove. She turned from pouring\
kerosene on the wood.\
\
\'93Good-by, Mrs. Garner,\'94 Nick said. \'93Thanks for taking me.\'94\
\
\'93Oh shucks, Nickie.\'94\
\
\'93I had a wonderful time.\'94\
\
\'93We like to have you. Won\'92t you stay and eat some supper?\'94\
\
\'93I better go. I think Dad probably waited for me.\'94\
\
\'93Well, get along then. Send Carl up to the house, will you?\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93Good-night, Nickie.\'94\
\
\'93Good-night, Mrs. Garner.\'94\
\
Nick went out the farmyard and down to the barn. Joe and Frank were\
milking.\
\
\'93Good-night,\'94 Nick said. \'93I had a swell time.\'94\
\
\'93Good-night, Nick,\'94 Joe Garner called. \'93Aren\'92t you going to stay and\
eat?\'94\
\
\'93No, I can\'92t. Will you tell Carl his mother wants him?\'94\
\
\'93All right. Good-night, Nickie.\'94\
\
Nick walked barefoot along the path through the meadow below the barn.\
The path was smooth and the dew was cool on his bare feet. He climbed a\
fence at the end of the meadow, went down through a ravine, his feet wet\
in the swamp mud, and then climbed up through the dry beech woods until\
he saw the lights of the cottage. He climbed over the fence and walked\
around to the front porch. Through the window he saw his father sitting\
by the table, reading in the light from the big lamp. Nick opened the\
door and went in.\
\
\'93Well, Nickie,\'94 his father said, \'93was it a good day?\'94\
\
\'93I had a swell time, Dad. It was a swell Fourth of July.\'94\
\
\'93Are you hungry?\'94\
\
\'93You bet.\'94\
\
\'93What did you do with your shoes?\'94\
\
\'93I left them in the wagon at Garner\'92s.\'94\
\
\'93Come on out to the kitchen.\'94\
\
Nick\'92s father went ahead with the lamp. He stopped and lifted the lid of\
the ice-box. Nick went on into the kitchen. His father brought in a\
piece of cold chicken on a plate and a pitcher of milk and put them on\
the table before Nick. He put down the lamp.\
\
\'93There\'92s some pie too,\'94 he said. \'93Will that hold you?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s grand.\'94\
\
His father sat down in a chair beside the oilcloth-covered table. He\
made a big shadow on the kitchen wall.\
\
\'93Who won the ball game?\'94\
\
\'93Petoskey. Five to three.\'94\
\
His father sat watching him eat and filled his glass from the\
milk-pitcher. Nick drank and wiped his mouth on his napkin. His father\
reached over to the shelf for the pie. He cut Nick a big piece. It was\
huckleberry pie.\
\
\'93What did you do, Dad?\'94\
\
\'93I went out fishing in the morning.\'94\
\
\'93What did you get?\'94\
\
\'93Only perch.\'94\
\
His father sat watching Nick eat the pie.\
\
\'93What did you do this afternoon?\'94 Nick asked.\
\
\'93I went for a walk up by the Indian camp.\'94\
\
\'93Did you see anybody?\'94\
\
\'93The Indians were all in town getting drunk.\'94\
\
\'93Didn\'92t you see anybody at all?\'94\
\
\'93I saw your friend, Prudie.\'94\
\
\'93Where was she?\'94\
\
\'93She was in the woods with Frank Washburn. I ran onto them. They were\
having quite a time.\'94\
\
His father was not looking at him.\
\
\'93What were they doing?\'94\
\
\'93I didn\'92t stay to find out.\'94\
\
\'93Tell me what they were doing.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know,\'94 his father said. \'93I just heard them threshing around.\'94\
\
\'93How did you know it was them?\'94\
\
\'93I saw them.\'94\
\
\'93I thought you said you didn\'92t see them.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes, I saw them.\'94\
\
\'93Who was it with her?\'94 Nick asked.\
\
\'93Frank Washburn.\'94\
\
\'93Were they\'97were they\'97\'97\'94\
\
\'93Were they what?\'94\
\
\'93Were they happy?\'94\
\
\'93I guess so.\'94\
\
His father got up from the table and went out the kitchen screen door.\
When he came back Nick was looking at his plate. He had been crying.\
\
\'93Have some more?\'94 His father picked up the knife to cut the pie.\
\
\'93No,\'94 said Nick.\
\
\'93You better have another piece.\'94\
\
\'93No, I don\'92t want any.\'94\
\
His father cleared off the table.\
\
\'93Where were they in the woods?\'94 Nick asked.\
\
\'93Up back of the camp.\'94 Nick looked at his plate. His father said, \'93You\
better go to bed, Nick.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
Nick went into his room, undressed, and got into bed. He heard his\
father moving around in the living-room. Nick lay in the bed with his\
face in the pillow.\
\
\'93My heart\'92s broken,\'94 he thought. \'93If I feel this way my heart must be\
broken.\'94\
\
After a while he heard his father blow out the lamp and go into his own\
room. He heard a wind come up in the trees outside and felt it come in\
cool through the screen. He lay for a long time with his face in the\
pillow, and after a while he forgot to think about Prudence and finally\
he went to sleep. When he awoke in the night he heard the wind in the\
hemlock trees outside the cottage and the waves of the lake coming in on\
the shore, and he went back to sleep. In the morning there was a big\
wind blowing and the waves were running high up on the beach and he was\
awake a long time before he remembered that his heart was broken.\
\
