                             A PURSUIT RACE\
\
\
WILLIAM CAMPBELL had been in a pursuit race with a burlesque show ever\
since Pittsburgh. In a pursuit race, in bicycle racing, riders start at\
equal intervals to ride after one another. They ride very fast because\
the race is usually limited to a short distance and if they slow their\
riding another rider who maintains his pace will make up the space that\
separated them equally at the start. As soon as a rider is caught and\
passed he is out of the race and must get down from his bicycle and\
leave the track. If none of the riders are caught the winner of the race\
is the one who has gained the most distance. In most pursuit races, if\
there are only two riders, one of the riders is caught inside of six\
miles. The burlesque show caught William Campbell at Kansas City.\
\
William Campbell had hoped to hold a slight lead over the burlesque show\
until they reached the Pacific coast. As long as he preceded the\
burlesque show as advance man he was being paid. When the burlesque show\
caught up with him he was in bed. He was in bed when the manager of the\
burlesque troupe came into his room and after the manager had gone out\
he decided that he might as well stay in bed. It was very cold in Kansas\
City and he was in no hurry to go out. He did not like Kansas City. He\
reached under the bed for a bottle and drank. It made his stomach feel\
better. Mr. Turner, the manager of the burlesque show, had refused a\
drink.\
\
William Campbell\'92s interview with Mr. Turner had been a little strange.\
Mr. Turner had knocked on the door. Campbell had said: \'93Come in!\'94 When\
Mr. Turner came into the room he saw clothing on a chair, an open\
suitcase, the bottle on a chair beside the bed, and some one lying in\
the bed completely covered by the bed-clothes.\
\
\'93Mister Campbell,\'94 Mr. Turner said.\
\
\'93You can\'92t fire me,\'94 William Campbell said from underneath the covers.\
It was warm and white and close under the covers. \'93You can\'92t fire me\
because I\'92ve got down off my bicycle.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re drunk,\'94 Mr. Turner said.\
\
\'93Oh, yes,\'94 William Campbell said, speaking directly against the sheet\
and feeling the texture with his lips.\
\
\'93You\'92re a fool,\'94 Mr. Turner said. He turned off the electric light. The\
electric light had been burning all night. It was now ten o\'92clock in the\
morning. \'93You\'92re a drunken fool. When did you get into this town?\'94\
\
\'93I got into this town last night,\'94 William Campbell said, speaking\
against the sheet. He found he liked to talk through a sheet. \'93Did you\
ever talk through a sheet?\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t try to be funny. You aren\'92t funny.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not being funny. I\'92m just talking through a sheet.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re talking through a sheet all right.\'94\
\
\'93You can go now, Mr. Turner,\'94 Campbell said. \'93I don\'92t work for you any\
more.\'94\
\
\'93You know that anyway.\'94\
\
\'93I know a lot,\'94 William Campbell said. He pulled down the sheet and\
looked at Mr. Turner. \'93I know enough so I don\'92t mind looking at you at\
all. Do you want to hear what I know?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93Good,\'94 said William Campbell. \'93Because really I don\'92t know anything at\
all. I was just talking.\'94 He pulled the sheet up over his face again. \'93I\
love it under a sheet,\'94 he said. Mr. Turner stood beside the bed. He was\
a middle-aged man with a large stomach and a bald head and he had many\
things to do. \'93You ought to stop off here, Billy, and take a cure,\'94 he\
said. \'93I\'92ll fix it up if you want to do it.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want to take a cure,\'94 William Campbell said. \'93I don\'92t want to\
take a cure at all. I am perfectly happy. All my life I have been\
perfectly happy.\'94\
\
\'93How long have you been this way?\'94\
\
\'93What a question!\'94 William Campbell breathed in and out through the\
sheet.\
\
\'93How long have you been stewed, Billy?\'94\
\
\'93Haven\'92t I done my work?\'94\
\
\'93Sure. I just asked you how long you\'92ve been stewed, Billy.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. But I\'92ve got my wolf back,\'94 he touched the sheet with his\
tongue. \'93I\'92ve had him for a week.\'94\
\
\'93The hell you have.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes. My dear wolf. Every time I take a drink he goes outside the\
room. He can\'92t stand alcohol. The poor little fellow.\'94 He moved his\
tongue round and round on the sheet. \'93He\'92s a lovely wolf. He\'92s just like\
he always was.\'94 William Campbell shut his eyes and took a deep breath.\
\
\'93You got to take a cure, Billy,\'94 Mr. Turner said. \'93You won\'92t mind the\
Keeley. It isn\'92t bad.\'94\
\
\'93The Keeley,\'94 William Campbell said. \'93It isn\'92t far from London.\'94 He shut\
his eyes and opened them, moving the eyelashes against the sheet. \'93I\
just love sheets,\'94 he said. He looked at Mr. Turner.\
\
\'93Listen, you think I\'92m drunk.\'94\
\
\'93You _are_ drunk.\'94\
\
\'93No, I\'92m not.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re drunk and you\'92ve had dt\'92s.\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94 William Campbell held the sheet around his head. \'93Dear sheet,\'94 he\
said. He breathed against it gently. \'93Pretty sheet. You love me, don\'92t\
you, sheet? It\'92s all in the price of the room. Just like in Japan. No,\'94\
he said. \'93Listen Billy, dear Sliding Billy, I have a surprise for you.\
I\'92m not drunk. I\'92m hopped to the eyes.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 said Mr. Turner.\
\
\'93Take a look.\'94 William Campbell pulled up the right sleeve of his pyjama\
jacket under the sheet, then shoved the right forearm out. \'93Look at\
that.\'94 On the forearm, from just above the wrist to the elbow, were\
small blue circles around tiny dark blue punctures. The circles almost\
touched one another. \'93That\'92s the new development,\'94 William Campbell\
said. \'93I drink a little now once in a while, just to drive the wolf out\
of the room.\'94\
\
\'93They got a cure for that, \'91Sliding Billy\'92\'94 Turner said.\
\
\'93No,\'94 William Campbell said. \'93They haven\'92t got a cure for anything.\'94\
\
\'93You can\'92t just quit like that, Billy,\'94 Turner said. He sat on the bed.\
\
\'93Be careful of my sheet,\'94 William Campbell said.\
\
\'93You can\'92t just quit at your age and take to pumping yourself full of\
that stuff just because you got in a jam.\'94\
\
\'93There\'92s a law against it. If that\'92s what you mean.\'94\
\
\'93No, I mean you got to fight it out.\'94\
\
Billy Campbell caressed the sheet with his lips and his tongue. \'93Dear\
sheet,\'94 he said. \'93I can kiss this sheet and see right through it at the\
same time.\'94\
\
\'93Cut it out about the sheet. You can\'92t just take to that stuff, Billy.\'94\
\
William Campbell shut his eyes. He was beginning to feel a slight\
nausea. He knew that this nausea would increase steadily, without there\
ever being the relief of sickness, until something were done against it.\
It was at this point that he suggested that Mr. Turner have a drink. Mr.\
Turner declined. William Campbell took a drink from the bottle. It was a\
temporary measure. Mr. Turner watched him. Mr. Turner had been in this\
room much longer than he should have been, he had many things to do;\
although living in daily association with people who used drugs, he had\
a horror of drugs, and he was very fond of William Campbell; he did not\
wish to leave him. He was very sorry for him and he felt a cure might\
help. He knew there were good cures in Kansas City. But he had to go. He\
stood up.\
\
\'93Listen, Billy,\'94 William Campbell said, \'93I want to tell you something.\
You\'92re called \'91Sliding Billy.\'92 That\'92s because you can slide. I\'92m called\
just Billy. That\'92s because I never could slide at all. I can\'92t slide,\
Billy. I can\'92t slide. It just catches. Every time I try it, it catches.\'94\
He shut his eyes. \'93I can\'92t slide, Billy. It\'92s awful when you can\'92t\
slide.\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 said \'93Sliding Billy\'94 Turner.\
\
\'93Yes, what?\'94 William Campbell looked at him.\
\
\'93You were saying.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 said William Campbell. \'93I wasn\'92t saying. It must have been a\
mistake.\'94\
\
\'93You were saying about sliding.\'94\
\
\'93No. It couldn\'92t have been about sliding. But listen, Billy, and I\'92ll\
tell you a secret. Stick to sheets, Billy. Keep away from women and\
horses and, and\'97\'94 he stopped \'93\'97eagles, Billy. If you love horses\
you\'92ll get horse-s\'97, and if you love eagles you\'92ll get eagle-s\'97.\'94 He\
stopped and put his head under the sheet.\
\
\'93I got to go,\'94 said \'93Sliding Billy\'94 Turner.\
\
\'93If you love women you\'92ll get a dose,\'94 William Campbell said. \'93If you\
love horses\'97\'97\'94\
\
\'93Yes, you said that.\'94\
\
\'93Said what?\'94\
\
\'93About horses and eagles.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes. And if you love sheets.\'94 He breathed on the sheet and stroked\
his nose against it. \'93I don\'92t know about sheets,\'94 he said. \'93I just\
started to love this sheet.\'94\
\
\'93I have to go,\'94 Mr. Turner said. \'93I got a lot to do.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s all right,\'94 William Campbell said. \'93Everybody\'92s got to go.\'94\
\
\'93I better go.\'94\
\
\'93All right, you go.\'94\
\
\'93Are you all right, Billy?\'94\
\
\'93I was never so happy in my life.\'94\
\
\'93And you\'92re all right?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m fine. You go along. I\'92ll just lie here for a little while. Around\
noon I\'92ll get up.\'94\
\
But when Mr. Turner came up to William Campbell\'92s room at noon William\
Campbell was sleeping and as Mr. Turner was a man who knew what things\
in life were very valuable he did not wake him.\
